03:06.438 --> 03:08.607
Woman: Non-fat,
no-foam latte for Maura.

03:08.708 --> 03:10.075
Thank you.

03:12.411 --> 03:16.281
- Triple latte for Claire.
- Thank you. Have a lovely day.

03:16.382 --> 03:18.449
Excuse me. 
I ordered before her.

03:18.484 --> 03:21.953
- Double-frap, no whip for Bill.
- Thank you.

03:21.987 --> 03:24.323
- And I ordered before him.
- Be patient.

03:24.357 --> 03:29.295
- She says, as she drinks her latte.
- I'm gonna go get some stevia.

03:29.329 --> 03:31.297
I'm gonna watch people
who ordered after me

03:31.331 --> 03:32.899
get their coffee before me.

03:35.936 --> 03:39.239
Oh, I love your outfit.
It's so cute.

03:39.273 --> 03:40.974
- Thank you.
- You're welcome.

03:41.008 --> 03:42.409
Have you seen the stevia?

03:42.443 --> 03:45.678
Yeah. Right here.
Oh, love this stuff.

03:45.746 --> 03:47.847
Double-shot espresso for Reggie.

03:47.915 --> 03:49.115
- Hey, thanks.
- You're welcome.

03:49.150 --> 03:51.117
[ cellphone vibrates ]

03:51.151 --> 03:52.952
Hey, we got a call.

03:52.987 --> 03:55.188
How long ... did you go to Costa
Rica to get the coffee beans?

03:55.222 --> 03:57.023
How long does it take to make a latte?

03:57.058 --> 04:00.660
Some people are so grumpy.
Jane.

04:00.695 --> 04:02.129
Thank you.

04:02.163 --> 04:03.430
<i>Half-caf non-fat latte for Jeff.</i>

04:03.464 --> 04:06.166
First I'm freezing,
and then I'm sweating.

04:06.201 --> 04:08.969
It's like, global
warming is so upsetting.

04:09.004 --> 04:10.437
Excuse me.

04:10.472 --> 04:13.340
Excuse me.

04:13.441 --> 04:15.710
[ louder ] Excuse me.

04:15.811 --> 04:18.846
I-I didn't hear you.
You don't have to be rude.

04:18.880 --> 04:22.151
- Just trying to get to work.
- Well, someone's in a bad mood.

04:22.219 --> 04:25.488
It'd be better if you would
just share the milk and sugar.

04:25.522 --> 04:26.989
Okay. All right.

04:30.060 --> 04:31.861
[ grunts ]

04:31.896 --> 04:33.296
- Oh, my gosh, I'm so sorry.
- Oh, god.

04:33.330 --> 04:34.864
- What happened?
- Oh, my gosh.

04:34.899 --> 04:36.165
Oh, my god, what ...
Jane, what happened?

04:36.200 --> 04:38.034
Oh, your friend threw her coffee at me.

04:38.069 --> 04:40.370
No. No, no, no. I-I didn't.
It was an accident. I'm so sorry.

04:40.471 --> 04:41.871
It was on purpose.

04:41.906 --> 04:44.874
- No, no. You bumped into me. I'm s...
- I bumped into you? You burned me.

04:44.909 --> 04:47.210
I mean, I wasn't moving
fast enough for you.

04:47.244 --> 04:48.511
I'm really, really sorry. Are you okay?

04:48.545 --> 04:50.079
Are you burned?

04:50.180 --> 04:51.513
Don't touch me. Don't...
don't touch me again.

04:51.548 --> 04:52.881
I didn't touch you at all. Don't ...

04:52.916 --> 04:54.816
I'm a doctor. Can I ... 
can I help you?

04:54.851 --> 04:57.052
Just ... everyone just
get away from me, okay?

04:57.120 --> 05:00.222
- It was an accident.
- Okay, Jane. Let's just go.

05:00.256 --> 05:02.257
<i>What a bitch.</i>

05:02.325 --> 05:05.728
Okay.
Let's just get out of here.

05:05.762 --> 05:08.164
- I didn't mean to.
- Of course you didn't.

05:08.198 --> 05:10.266
- And I didn't get any coffee.
- Here, take mine.

05:10.334 --> 05:14.437
- What about you?
- It's okay. Let's go.

05:14.491 --> 05:16.892
<i>[ sirens wailing ]
Reporter: It's a fluid situation</i>

05:16.927 --> 05:18.727
<i>in this usually quiet
Boston neighborhood.</i>

05:18.762 --> 05:20.930
<i>What we know so far ... an
elderly man holed up inside...</i>

05:20.998 --> 05:24.233
<i>Reporter #2: That's right, Denise.
We've just arrived at the scene</i>

05:24.268 --> 05:26.269
of a tense standoff between an
elderly man and Boston police.

05:26.370 --> 05:28.604
Wow. 
Homicide's running the scene?

05:28.671 --> 05:30.072
Only till SWAT gets here.

05:30.106 --> 05:32.341
We think the guy in the
standoff killed somebody inside.

05:32.375 --> 05:34.210
<i>Charlie: Sir, please, step back.</i>

05:36.346 --> 05:38.047
Dude... who's that?

05:38.081 --> 05:41.217
Damn. She must be from
the new crop of rookies.

05:41.251 --> 05:43.186
Does she know how hot she is?

05:43.220 --> 05:45.254
Why don't you go over
there and tell her?

05:45.289 --> 05:46.923
Detective.

05:47.024 --> 05:50.759
Stop checking out the pretty
cop and make yourselves useful.

05:50.794 --> 05:52.027
I need eyes around the back.

05:52.062 --> 05:53.629
<i>Man: Hey, e-excuse me.</i>

05:53.697 --> 05:55.097
Any idea how long my
street's gonna be blocked?

05:55.132 --> 05:57.366
Might be a few hours.
Do you know the guy in the house?

05:57.434 --> 06:01.204
- Leroy? Uh, he's crazy.
- What do you mean by crazy?

06:01.238 --> 06:04.374
You know, nut-ball conspiracy theorist.
He's always going off

06:04.408 --> 06:07.110
about, uh, U.F.O.s and
government spies and...

06:07.144 --> 06:09.746
Well, I guess I better
call my office, huh?

06:09.780 --> 06:12.115
Officer Hansen?
 Let me introduce you.

06:12.149 --> 06:14.250
Detectives, this is
officer Charlotte Hansen.

06:14.285 --> 06:16.253
Oh, Charlie. 
Nice to meet you.

06:16.287 --> 06:17.621
We need eyes in the back.

06:17.622 --> 06:20.123
Take Charlie, show her the ropes.
I'll be out front.

06:20.157 --> 06:21.124
- Yeah. Right here.
- Okay.

06:21.158 --> 06:23.259
[ helicopter blades whirring ]

06:25.229 --> 06:27.464
[ siren chirps ]

06:27.498 --> 06:29.432
[ police radio chatter ]

06:32.169 --> 06:34.805
Oh. You look like you've
already had a bad morning.

06:34.839 --> 06:38.075
Me? Oh, no.
I haven't showered,

06:38.109 --> 06:39.843
I had a skeevy building
manager check out my boobs,

06:39.878 --> 06:42.246
I spilled 16 ounces of hot
coffee on some perfect stranger.

06:42.280 --> 06:43.681
Yeah, no, I'm great.

06:43.748 --> 06:46.284
- Operations said there was a body inside?
- Well, all we know for sure

06:46.318 --> 06:47.952
is what the gunman
told the 911 operator.

06:48.019 --> 06:49.420
<i>Operator: 911. What is your emergency?</i>

06:49.454 --> 06:51.188
<i>Leroy: They're watching
me, stealing from me!</i>

06:51.256 --> 06:54.091
<i>Sir, please stay calm.
I need your address.</i>

06:54.125 --> 06:56.360
<i>[ voice breaking ]
Oh, no, no. Daniel's dead.</i>

06:56.394 --> 06:59.129
It's possible he's suffering
from persecutory delusions.

06:59.164 --> 07:00.731
Who's Daniel?

07:00.765 --> 07:02.199
We think it's a sanitation
worker ... Daniel Raine.

07:02.267 --> 07:03.834
We found his truck at
the end of the block.

07:03.868 --> 07:06.436
- What do we know about the gunman?
- Leroy Grovner.

07:06.471 --> 07:09.106
72-year-old retired engineer,
lives alone, no relatives.

07:09.140 --> 07:11.175
Do we know if he's on any medications?

07:11.209 --> 07:12.777
Oh, he doesn't trust doctors.

07:12.811 --> 07:14.879
Last time he saw one was
in the E.R. six months ago.

07:14.947 --> 07:16.447
- Psychotic break?
- Broken hip.

07:16.481 --> 07:18.416
First responders said
they tried to talk to him

07:18.450 --> 07:21.886
but he said,  if he talks,
itwill only be to a lady cop.

07:21.920 --> 07:23.988
Stay away from my house!

07:29.060 --> 07:30.527
Oh! Oh! Oh! Hold your fire!

07:30.561 --> 07:34.197
- Hold your fire! You see what I see?
- Yeah. Smoke. He's shooting blanks.

07:34.232 --> 07:36.032
All right. Everybody just stand down.

07:36.067 --> 07:37.467
- Hey, stand down. He's shooting blanks.
- Maura, come on.

07:41.906 --> 07:43.841
It's all right ... easy.

07:43.875 --> 07:46.877
Mr. Grovner. It's okay.

07:46.911 --> 07:48.412
- What do you want?!
- It's all right, okay?

07:48.480 --> 07:50.848
We... we just want to ...
we want to help Daniel.

07:50.882 --> 07:54.251
Okay?
Can we do that, please?

07:54.319 --> 07:57.254
I'm a doctor. If you let me
see him, maybe I can help him.

07:57.355 --> 07:58.422
<i>Leroy: Oh.</i>

08:01.826 --> 08:02.826
Oh.

08:05.296 --> 08:07.330
Oh, all ... all right.

08:07.398 --> 08:11.267
But it ... b-but I-it's a ...
it's a mess down ... down there.

08:11.335 --> 08:13.870
Can I hold that for you?

08:13.904 --> 08:16.740
It's all right.
All right. Thank you.

08:16.774 --> 08:18.074
<i>Officer: Stand down!</i>

08:18.175 --> 08:20.410
All right. It's all right. 
You know what?

08:20.444 --> 08:23.413
Why ... why don't we go sit
down in one of the cars, okay?

08:23.447 --> 08:25.916
Why don't you take this?
Go check on Daniel.

08:25.950 --> 08:27.917
All right.

08:27.952 --> 08:31.420
- Let's ... just go right over here. Okay?
- Okay.

08:35.716 --> 08:38.355
- Jane: Maura?
- Down here.  

08:39.390 --> 08:42.313
- He's been dead for a few hours.
- When's the power coming back on?

08:42.347 --> 08:43.914
We get lost down here,
they're never gonna find us.

08:43.982 --> 08:46.016
Public works doesn't
know why it went off,

08:46.051 --> 08:48.318
so they're having a
hard time restoring it.

08:49.387 --> 08:51.222
Yeah. It's a garbage man, all right.

08:51.256 --> 08:54.225
Daniel Raine.
Works for the sanitation department.

08:54.259 --> 08:56.227
- What's he doing down here?
- Overtime?

08:56.261 --> 08:57.762
You have enough light?

08:57.830 --> 08:59.864
Enough to see a penetrating wound

08:59.898 --> 09:02.033
resulting in a subarachnoid hemorrhage.

09:02.067 --> 09:04.302
What's unusual is the wound pattern.

09:04.370 --> 09:06.771
Somebody hit him hard.
That's a lot of blood.

09:06.805 --> 09:09.340
What did they hit him with?
A lawn mower?

09:09.374 --> 09:11.809
Sewing machine? Crock-pot?

09:11.877 --> 09:14.145
I think we can rule out the crock-pot.

09:14.179 --> 09:17.248
Whatever it was, it had
a very sharp, jagged edge.

09:17.349 --> 09:20.018
We talked to the neighbors.
They said Leroy started screaming

09:20.052 --> 09:21.819
about space ships and little green men.

09:21.854 --> 09:24.355
Yeah, right after the lights went out.
Then he started shooting.

09:24.390 --> 09:27.092
Okay, so the aliens landed,
and he lost his marbles.

09:27.126 --> 09:30.762
Well, maybe they're down here.
Seems like everything else is.

09:30.797 --> 09:32.197
Except the murder weapon.

09:32.232 --> 09:34.233
All right, let's, uh,
let's start a search.

09:34.267 --> 09:38.070
<i>Korsak: Hey. An 8-track player.
And a flowbee.</i>

09:38.104 --> 09:41.173
- I always wanted one of these.
- Next birthday. On me.

09:41.207 --> 09:44.743
Jane: Hey, Korsak, let's you and I
go back and interrogate Leroy.

09:44.778 --> 09:46.334
Frost, Frankie, you
guys do the search, okay?

09:46.335 --> 09:47.112
- Frankie: Okay.
- Why me?

09:47.146 --> 09:49.948
Well, it's either hoarder
duty or liquor licenses for me.

09:49.983 --> 09:52.751
I'm gonna have to get this
body back to the morgue.

09:52.819 --> 09:55.187
Well, leave Frankie, then I can
start the background investigation.

09:55.222 --> 09:57.956
- All right.
- Charlie: Detectives. Need anything else?

09:57.991 --> 10:00.225
Uh, yeah. Detective Frost was just...

10:02.061 --> 10:05.363
- ...leaving.
- Well, I-I could use your help.

10:05.431 --> 10:07.065
Okay.

10:07.099 --> 10:10.067
You know what, Detective Frost?
Why don't you stay?

10:10.101 --> 10:14.338
Yeah. Yeah, uh, there's
a lot of work to do here.

10:14.406 --> 10:15.839
[ clears throat ]

10:15.907 --> 10:18.441
Yes, there's a lot of work to do here.

10:20.111 --> 10:22.945
[ gasps ] Crazy, right?
Almost 49,000 hits already.

10:22.980 --> 10:24.280
It's going totally viral.

10:24.315 --> 10:26.349
Okay, how do you get
it off of this thing?

10:26.384 --> 10:29.753
- I don't want people to see this.
- It's funny, Ma.

10:29.787 --> 10:33.123
Aww.
Isn't that nice?

10:33.157 --> 10:37.093
- Enjoying a video of your sweet daughter.
- You saw it?

10:37.127 --> 10:41.998
Several times, along with everyone
at headquarters. Let's see it again.

10:42.033 --> 10:43.700
- Oh.
- It really gives me a chuckle.

10:43.801 --> 10:45.468
<i>Woman: Someone's in a bad mood.</i>

10:45.503 --> 10:48.072
<i>You trying ... you trying ... you
trying ... [ chuckles ] [ sighs ]</i>

10:48.106 --> 10:49.173
<i>Jane: I didn't touch you at
all. I didn't touch you at all.</i>

10:49.207 --> 10:50.808
<i>Oh! Oh!
 [ groans ]</i>

10:50.842 --> 10:52.710
[ laughter ]

10:52.778 --> 10:54.378
Oh, you must be very proud.

10:54.446 --> 10:55.746
- It's awesome.
- Get away.

10:55.780 --> 10:58.482
She's gonna be famous, mom.
I'm gonna send her the link.

10:58.516 --> 11:00.283
Don't you do that!

11:00.318 --> 11:02.152
You catch the garbage
man stealing your stuff,

11:02.186 --> 11:03.453
you whack him over the head.

11:03.488 --> 11:05.189
Maybe you didn't mean
to hit him so hard.

11:05.223 --> 11:08.759
I don't like it in here.
I'm only talking to the nice lady.

11:10.962 --> 11:12.930
I got this.

11:15.266 --> 11:16.833
It's okay, Leroy. I'm here.

11:16.901 --> 11:18.935
Why don't you just
tell me what happened?

11:18.970 --> 11:22.305
Not you. You took my gun.
The nice doctor lady.

11:26.410 --> 11:30.846
<i>I'm Dr. Maura Isles.
Can you tell me your name?</i>

11:30.881 --> 11:32.281
<i>Leroy. Leroy Grovner.</i>

11:32.315 --> 11:35.084
- Hello, Mr. Grovner.
- <i>Jane: Let's start with...</i>

11:35.119 --> 11:36.452
"no one likes it when
someone steals your stuff."

11:36.487 --> 11:38.854
I don't see the value
in stating the obvious.

11:38.889 --> 11:41.324
But ... but it's ... it's
my name, and you asked.

11:41.391 --> 11:43.993
<i>Just say it.</i>

11:44.027 --> 11:47.964
I'm sure you felt frustrated
when your belongings were taken.

11:47.998 --> 11:52.435
I thought I was going crazy at first.
And I'm not crazy, you know.

11:52.470 --> 11:55.272
My things, they were
disappearing into thin air.

11:55.306 --> 11:57.340
But then I realized who it was ... them.

11:57.375 --> 11:59.042
- "Them"?
- Mm-hmm.

11:59.110 --> 12:02.112
<i>They've been sniffing
around, spying on me.</i>

12:02.146 --> 12:03.080
Ask him who.

12:03.148 --> 12:06.550
- Who's been spying?
- Them ... stealing and spying.

12:06.618 --> 12:08.252
- Who's "them"?
- I-I had to put a stop...

12:08.286 --> 12:10.154
Poor old guy, I wonder if he even knows.

12:10.188 --> 12:13.056
So, the next time I heard them over me,

12:13.091 --> 12:16.159
I used the bug zapper.
<i>Got them good.</i>

12:16.194 --> 12:18.228
Okay, ask him what he
means by "got them."

12:18.296 --> 12:20.531
- How did you get them?
- Took them down.

12:20.565 --> 12:23.501
They were mad. They came
looking for me because I had it.

12:23.535 --> 12:26.971
- You had what?
- They got ... they got Daniel instead.

12:27.005 --> 12:29.574
<i>Okay.
 Ask him about the bug zapper.</i>

12:29.642 --> 12:31.009
Is that the murder weapon?

12:31.043 --> 12:35.547
Leroy, is that how Daniel died?
You zapped him?

12:35.582 --> 12:37.950
No, I ... I didn't kill him.
He was my friend!

12:37.984 --> 12:40.319
He gave me good stuff from
his ... from his garbage route.

12:40.353 --> 12:43.389
He even gave me a TX-78 sump pump.

12:43.423 --> 12:45.424
You think Daniel was bringing
stuff for the basement, and then 

12:45.459 --> 12:48.160
- Leroy got confused and killed him?
- Yeah, maybe.

12:48.194 --> 12:50.496
I hate to speculate. We don't
know what Daniel was doing there.

12:50.530 --> 12:52.197
Hey, who are you talking to?

12:52.232 --> 12:53.632
- Are they here?
- I-I ...

12:53.667 --> 12:55.468
- They're here.
- No, Leroy. Nobody is here.

12:55.502 --> 12:57.470
<i>It's not gonna work.
You can't have my things!</i>

12:57.504 --> 13:00.339
How does a frail 79-year-old
with a hip fracture

13:00.373 --> 13:04.242
- take out a guy Daniel's size?
- Adrenaline? Fear?

13:04.277 --> 13:06.444
<i>No one's here but me.</i>

13:09.148 --> 13:11.115
[ police radio chatter ]

13:14.686 --> 13:18.622
That may be a killer ass, but
it's not the murder weapon.

13:20.925 --> 13:22.960
Yay.

13:22.994 --> 13:26.429
- Glad the power's back on.
- Yay.

13:26.497 --> 13:27.464
[ chuckles ]

13:27.498 --> 13:31.067
- She's not your type.
- Oh, oh, that's my type.

13:31.101 --> 13:34.904
- In your dreams.
- Well, so she's your type?

13:34.938 --> 13:38.474
She's exactly my type.
[ sighs ]

13:38.508 --> 13:40.109
I mean, do you guys know what
the murder weapon looks like?

13:40.143 --> 13:41.510
I'll have more information

13:41.545 --> 13:43.312
once I hear back from
the medical examiner,

13:43.346 --> 13:45.448
but look for anything that
could be used as a club.

13:45.515 --> 13:49.452
Okay, yeah. I'm getting a lot of
electric blankets and blenders.

13:49.486 --> 13:52.855
Me, too. I mean, I-I got a
pogo stick, a dentist drill.

13:52.889 --> 13:53.956
[ chuckles ]

13:53.990 --> 13:58.360
- And... what the hell is this?
- Oh, my gosh. That's an aebleskiver pan.

13:58.394 --> 14:02.197
My grandma, she's Norwegian.
Uh, she makes them all the time.

14:02.232 --> 14:03.666
They're, like, these
cute little pancake balls.

14:03.700 --> 14:06.035
Yum. 
Introduce me to your grandmother.

14:06.069 --> 14:07.336
Okay. [ chuckles ]

14:09.539 --> 14:15.277
- Uh, so, do we just bag it all, or...
- [ clears throat ] Um, well, uh...

14:15.312 --> 14:19.048
He's pretty junior.
I'm in homicide, so...

14:19.082 --> 14:22.485
let's bag everything
near where the body was.

14:22.519 --> 14:25.054
Got it.

14:25.155 --> 14:27.423
Whoa, sir. 
This is a crime scene.

14:27.458 --> 14:29.258
Oh, no, it's okay. I live next door.

14:29.359 --> 14:31.961
No, it isn't okay.
 I need to ask you to leave now.

14:31.995 --> 14:35.098
I, uh, brought you some lemonade.
I thought you guys might be thirsty.

14:35.165 --> 14:37.066
No. We're not thirsty.
Come on. Let's go.

14:37.101 --> 14:38.935
Yeah, well, why don't I...
I'll just leave it here?

14:39.002 --> 14:40.736
You can bring the pitcher back later.

14:40.770 --> 14:42.938
The yellow house with
the white picket fence.

14:42.973 --> 14:44.607
No, you can't leave that here. 
Come on.

14:44.708 --> 14:45.541
- Oh.
- Let's go.

14:45.575 --> 14:47.275
Oh, sure. Yeah, yeah.

14:47.343 --> 14:50.746
Oh, listen, uh, Leroy, uh,
borrowed a bunch of stuff

14:50.780 --> 14:52.948
over the years and never returned it,

14:53.016 --> 14:57.387
so if you happen to come
across a metric wrench set

14:57.421 --> 15:01.190
<i>or, uh, a pair of old hockey skates,
uh, I'd really like to get them back.</i>

15:01.225 --> 15:03.459
- We'll keep an eye out.
- Yeah.

15:03.561 --> 15:06.629
Oh, yeah.

15:09.266 --> 15:10.734
[ door closes ]

15:12.970 --> 15:15.338
He was struck at least
twice, and whatever

15:15.339 --> 15:17.707
instrument was used left
an odd pattern in the wound.

15:17.741 --> 15:20.310
Leroy had enough odd crap in his house

15:20.377 --> 15:22.545
to keep craigslist in business
for the next 2,000 years.

15:22.580 --> 15:24.948
Can you narrow it down?

15:24.982 --> 15:27.584
Hmm.
It's interesting.

15:27.619 --> 15:30.521
Symmetrical linked
hexagons, like a honeycomb.

15:30.588 --> 15:32.156
Would be the first time anybody died

15:32.190 --> 15:34.258
from being bashed in
the head with a beehive.

15:34.292 --> 15:36.260
It's not a beehive.

15:36.295 --> 15:40.364
I'm putting my money on
an electric toothbrush.

15:40.399 --> 15:43.601
Or maybe the knitting machine.

15:44.736 --> 15:47.005
You know, I've never
seen anything like it.

15:47.072 --> 15:49.007
Gonna have Susie take a look
and see what she can find

15:49.074 --> 15:51.476
in the tool-mark
identification database.

15:51.510 --> 15:53.745
- Okay.
- There's particulate in the wound.

15:53.812 --> 15:58.282
- I'll run it through GCMs.
- Okay. [ computer chimes ]

15:58.317 --> 15:59.684
Oh. That's Frost and Frankie.

15:59.718 --> 16:01.452
Want to tell them what to look for.

16:05.524 --> 16:06.624
<i>Hey, Dr. Isles.</i>

16:06.658 --> 16:09.427
<i>We're still sorting through junk.
Nothing promising so far.</i>

16:09.461 --> 16:10.795
Well, the murder weapon

16:10.829 --> 16:13.264
is approximately the
size of a baseball bat.

16:13.298 --> 16:15.500
Yeah, and it has a
beehive attached to it.

16:15.534 --> 16:17.201
<i>A who?</i>

16:17.236 --> 16:18.769
It has an edge that will
look like a honeycomb.

16:18.804 --> 16:21.839
<i>So... it's not robotman?</i>

16:21.874 --> 16:23.708
You know what, Frankie?

16:23.742 --> 16:25.810
Why don't you try acting
like a real Detective?

16:25.845 --> 16:28.212
<i>Oh, you mean like this?</i>

16:28.247 --> 16:29.547
<i>[ deep voice ] Out of my way,</i>

16:29.648 --> 16:31.716
<i>or I'm gonna throw my
extra-hot triple latte on you!</i>

16:31.783 --> 16:34.652
<i>[ high-pitched voice ] 
Oh, no! Please don't, officer!</i>

16:34.686 --> 16:36.454
<i>[ roars ] 
[ screams ]</i>

16:36.488 --> 16:38.689
Wait a minute. How do
you know about that?

16:38.723 --> 16:39.723
<i>You haven't seen it?</i>

16:39.758 --> 16:40.858
Seen what?

16:40.892 --> 16:42.859
<i>Go on youtube.
[ laughs ]</i>

16:42.893 --> 16:44.694
[ sighs ]

16:44.729 --> 16:46.529
Okay.

16:46.564 --> 16:51.634
<i>Okay, now type in
"mean Detective Jane."</i>

16:54.137 --> 16:56.805
[ keyboard clacking ]

16:56.873 --> 16:58.273
<i>[ siren wails ]</i>

16:58.341 --> 16:59.508
<i>I didn't touch you at all.</i>

16:59.542 --> 17:01.677
<i>Oh! Oh! Oh!
[ Groans ]</i>

17:01.711 --> 17:03.312
<i>It was on purpose.</i>

17:03.347 --> 17:04.547
<i>You know what? Don't... 
don't touch me again.</i>

17:04.580 --> 17:05.882
<i>I didn't touch you at all.</i>

17:05.915 --> 17:08.050
<i>- What a bitch.
- Here, take mine.</i>

17:08.085 --> 17:09.551
<i>Oh!</i>

17:09.587 --> 17:12.122
Wait. No. 
I didn't say that!

17:12.156 --> 17:15.425
They must have lip-dubbed you.
That is expert editing.

17:15.459 --> 17:18.094
Okay, wait, now you're an
expert on viral videos, too?

17:18.162 --> 17:19.362
<i>Come on, it's funny.</i>

17:29.432 --> 17:32.968
<i>Woman: Oh! Oh! Oh!
[ groans ] </i>

17:33.003 --> 17:34.370
<i>It was on purpose.</i>

17:34.438 --> 17:36.472
<i>You know what? Don't
... don't touch me again.</i>

17:41.111 --> 17:42.511
[ chuckling ]

17:42.545 --> 17:43.645
<i>Oh! Oh! Oh!
 [ groans ]</i>

17:43.680 --> 17:44.613
Et tu, Brute?

17:44.681 --> 17:48.184
- Well, it is kind of funny.
- Not if you're me.

17:50.020 --> 17:54.024
- Hi, honey.
- Oh, yay. I'm pregnant.

17:54.058 --> 17:56.426
Don't I have to have sex to be pregnant?

17:56.461 --> 17:57.861
Okay, for heaven's sake,

17:57.895 --> 17:59.897
we had a party for
Darlene in accounting.

17:59.931 --> 18:01.866
I thought you could
use some cheering up.

18:01.900 --> 18:03.234
Why would I need cheering up?

18:03.301 --> 18:05.036
Just because my video is more popular

18:05.070 --> 18:06.537
than that monkey flinging his poop?

18:06.605 --> 18:09.607
- So, you spilled a little coffee.
- Or threw it.

18:09.641 --> 18:11.342
I did not throw it!

18:11.376 --> 18:14.311
Mm, in slo-mo, it kind of
looks like you might've.

18:14.346 --> 18:18.916
Okay. I'm going to leave this
in case you want any later.

18:18.984 --> 18:21.418
- None for you!
- Thanks, Ma.

18:22.754 --> 18:26.190
Okay, turn that off or I will
throw Darlene's cake at you.

18:26.224 --> 18:29.059
What do we know about Leroy?

18:29.094 --> 18:33.530
Well...
Leroy was telling the truth.

18:33.565 --> 18:36.200
He and Daniel were friends.

18:36.234 --> 18:38.235
Leroy seems harmless. My
gut says he's no killer.

18:38.270 --> 18:39.971
Yeah, me too.

18:40.005 --> 18:42.072
But we're putting him in
lockup with a bunch of creeps.

18:42.107 --> 18:43.874
All right, so let's get
him a psych eval, buy him

18:43.875 --> 18:45.642
some time in the hospital.
At least he'll stay alive.

18:45.710 --> 18:47.111
- Good idea.
- What about Frost and Frankie?

18:47.178 --> 18:48.479
They come up with the murder weapon yet?

18:48.513 --> 18:50.214
Not yet.

18:50.248 --> 18:51.982
Stuff's coming into the crime
lab for processing, though.

18:52.017 --> 18:55.519
Why don't we remove the pretty
rookie and they can get focused?

18:55.553 --> 18:58.221
Another good idea.
I'll call it in.

18:58.256 --> 19:00.023
[ police radio chatter ]

19:00.058 --> 19:02.593
Echo 4-0-2. 
I'm off on an L-20 here.

19:03.627 --> 19:05.128
Frankie!

19:05.196 --> 19:07.197
- Yeah.
- Frankie, look at this.

19:07.232 --> 19:12.602
- What is it?
- I think Leroy made an E.M.P. gun.

19:12.637 --> 19:15.405
An electromagnetic pulse gun?

19:15.439 --> 19:17.573
Yeah, with an old-school approach.

19:17.608 --> 19:20.476
- Does it work?
- I don't know.

19:20.544 --> 19:22.212
Maybe we should find out.

19:23.114 --> 19:24.647
[ chuckles ]

19:24.715 --> 19:28.385
Echo 4-0-2.
 I'm off on an L-20 here.

19:28.419 --> 19:31.488
- Where you gonna aim it?
- Uh, definitely not at the houses.

19:31.589 --> 19:33.123
Uh, maybe there?

19:33.157 --> 19:34.958
<i>Dispatcher: Echo 4-0-2.
They want you back...</i>

19:34.992 --> 19:36.059
Go for it.

19:36.094 --> 19:37.294
<i>Charlie: 10-4. On my way.</i>

19:37.328 --> 19:39.396
[ electricity crackles ]

19:39.430 --> 19:40.564
Hello?

19:40.598 --> 19:43.367
Ah, I think we just took out the
electrical systems in the cruisers.

19:43.401 --> 19:46.103
Uh, that could be expensive.
Let's get back in the basement.

19:47.739 --> 19:49.406
Oh, hey, you guys?

19:49.440 --> 19:53.410
Uh, something just happened
to the radio in my car.

19:53.445 --> 19:57.247
- Weird.
- Oh, that happens all the time.

19:57.282 --> 20:00.517
Oh. Phew. [ chuckles ]
Thought I did something.

20:00.585 --> 20:03.487
Just call the guys in the shop.
They'll take care of it.

20:03.522 --> 20:04.689
Okay. Thanks.

20:12.331 --> 20:15.299
Why don't you talk to him, nice lady?

20:16.334 --> 20:20.305
- Hello, Leroy.
- Ah.

20:20.339 --> 20:22.607
- Is that my stuff?
- Yes.

20:22.641 --> 20:26.144
- Better all be there.
- It was all inventoried,

20:26.178 --> 20:27.812
but why don't you check
through it to make sure?

20:29.215 --> 20:30.582
I want to go home.

20:30.650 --> 20:33.385
They're probably in there
right now, taking my things.

20:33.419 --> 20:35.820
Mr. Grovner, you understand
you're not being released?

20:35.855 --> 20:37.422
The judge has ordered

20:37.456 --> 20:38.856
that you have an
evaluation at a hospital.

20:38.890 --> 20:40.825
Yeah, 'cause they all
think I'm ... I'm crazy.

20:40.892 --> 20:42.760
Everyone thinks I'm crazy. 
I'm not crazy.

20:42.795 --> 20:44.429
I believe you.

20:44.463 --> 20:46.598
I'll do anything to prove
I didn't kill Daniel.

20:46.632 --> 20:48.800
He wasn't stealing from
me. It was someone else.

20:48.835 --> 20:52.738
Uh, can I borrow your notepad?

20:52.806 --> 20:54.840
Thanks.

20:54.874 --> 20:59.078
Mr. Grovner, why don't
you describe to me

20:59.146 --> 21:01.281
the items that you're missing?

21:01.349 --> 21:04.351
Um, my, uh, my circuit boards,

21:04.385 --> 21:07.821
a-a-and an antique bird
cage, and hockey stuff.

21:07.855 --> 21:10.891
- Circuit boards, antique?
- Yeah.

21:10.925 --> 21:13.694
- Bird cage. Hockey equipment.
- Uh-huh.

21:13.728 --> 21:15.662
My dad was an equipment
manager for a hockey team.

21:15.696 --> 21:18.398
Saved all of it and gave
it to me before he died.

21:18.433 --> 21:22.101
Yeah? Okay.
I'll file an incident report

21:22.136 --> 21:23.336
And see if I can get
you your things back.

21:23.370 --> 21:24.504
[ chuckles ]

21:24.572 --> 21:28.808
- I'm ... I'm sorry.
- Why do you say that?

21:28.842 --> 21:32.545
I thought that you weren't
a nice lady, but ... but you are.

21:32.613 --> 21:35.615
Thank you.

21:36.851 --> 21:40.353
Okay. Come on, Leroy.
You're gonna be just fine.

21:40.388 --> 21:41.788
[ elevator bell dings ]
 [ grunts ]

21:41.856 --> 21:44.357
<i>Rizzoli.</i>

21:44.392 --> 21:49.896
- Yes, sir.
- In my office ... now.

21:49.964 --> 21:53.533
Is it too late to call in sick?

21:53.567 --> 21:59.405
- You want a union rep?
- Why, do I need one?

21:59.439 --> 22:03.575
Well... you might.

22:03.610 --> 22:05.777
<i>[ up-tempo music plays, siren wails ]</i>

22:05.879 --> 22:07.312
<i>[ auto-tuned ] 
Excuse me. Excuse me.</i>

22:07.380 --> 22:08.514
<i>[ auto-tuned ] 
Someone's in a bad mood.</i>

22:08.548 --> 22:10.382
<i>Just trying to get to work.</i>

22:10.416 --> 22:11.283
<i>[ sighs ] Get away ... get away ... 
get away from me.</i>

22:11.351 --> 22:12.784
<i>Don't t-t-touch me.</i>

22:14.287 --> 22:16.722
<i>B-b-b-b-bitch.</i>

22:16.756 --> 22:19.958
- It was an accident.
- Yeah, we all know that,

22:19.992 --> 22:22.194
but that woman says you
gave her second-degree burns.

22:22.228 --> 22:23.962
Oh, my god. [ scoffs ]

22:23.997 --> 22:26.398
- We have to investigate you.
- What? Why?

22:26.432 --> 22:29.501
Because she's filed a
police-brutality complaint against you.

22:32.805 --> 22:35.574
<i>- It's not the end of the world.
- Yeah, I know.</i>

22:35.608 --> 22:38.610
I'd be amazed if anybody
outside BPD even saw it.

22:38.645 --> 22:41.580
It has 79,000 hits, Maura.

22:41.614 --> 22:44.282
Well, I'll bet you
they're mostly Europeans.

22:44.316 --> 22:46.184
Europeans? 
[ dog whines ]

22:46.218 --> 22:48.519
Hey, Coop.
Hey, Cooper. [ dog barks ]

22:48.554 --> 22:51.856
Hey ... Coop, it's me. 
What? [ whining ]

22:51.891 --> 22:55.527
Cooper. He must be
picking up on your anxiety.

22:55.595 --> 22:59.363
- My anxiety?
- Yeah, we're late for Mah-jongg.

22:59.431 --> 23:01.665
- Wait, what ... what anxiety?
- Uh, come on, Cooper.

23:01.700 --> 23:04.969
I'm not gonna let her spill
anything on you, I promise.

23:05.004 --> 23:07.372
So, Ms. Billings is European?

23:07.406 --> 23:08.740
Man: Oh, hey, look.

23:08.774 --> 23:11.543
It's that cop that
throws coffee at people.

23:11.611 --> 23:13.578
- Hey, all right, move along.
- Oh, yeah.

23:13.613 --> 23:15.747
Do you throw doughnuts at
little kids on school buses, too?

23:15.781 --> 23:17.349
Okay, that's harassment.

23:17.383 --> 23:19.351
Oh, yeah?
Why don't you come arrest me?

23:19.385 --> 23:22.354
No, ignore him. Come on.

23:22.388 --> 23:23.655
<i>I just want to take a shower.</i>

23:23.689 --> 23:25.457
<i>Just want to take a shower. 
That's it.</i>

23:25.492 --> 23:27.860
[ indistinct talking on television ]

23:27.961 --> 23:29.628
Yo, sista.

23:29.662 --> 23:32.264
Hey. [ sighs ]
Did Gilbert fix my water?

23:32.331 --> 23:34.966
- Gil is cool.
- Tommy, did he fix my water?

23:35.001 --> 23:36.568
I don't think so.

23:36.635 --> 23:38.470
He had to take another
call, but he did do that.

23:40.973 --> 23:43.375
Tommy! How could you let him do that?

23:43.409 --> 23:46.912
There's a leak in the building, Jane.
It might even be black mold.

23:46.980 --> 23:49.448
Think we'll have to
wear those mask thingies?

23:49.516 --> 23:52.886
- I don't see any signs of mold.
- How am I supposed to take a shower?

23:52.920 --> 23:54.687
Jane, come on. 
You can stay at my place.

23:54.722 --> 23:57.057
Gil was asking about you.
I think he likes you.

23:57.091 --> 23:58.425
Swell.

23:58.493 --> 23:59.893
Oh, oh, here it is. Here it is.

24:01.362 --> 24:03.663
<i>And if you think you've had a bad day,</i>

24:03.698 --> 24:06.400
<i>be glad you're not Boston
Detective Jane Rizzoli,</i>

24:06.434 --> 24:07.901
<i>who finds herself in hot water</i>

24:07.969 --> 24:11.271
<i>after spilling scalding
coffee on a stranger.</i>

24:11.339 --> 24:12.806
- Is he? Is that?
- We talked to her brother

24:12.840 --> 24:14.941
<i>To find out if there
is more to this story.</i>

24:14.975 --> 24:16.843
<i>Oh, Jane has a temper, all right.</i>

24:16.877 --> 24:20.513
<i>Oh, yeah. When we were growing
up, nobody messed with us,</i>

24:20.581 --> 24:23.582
<i>'cause if they did, Jane would
kick the crap out of them.</i>

24:23.617 --> 24:25.017
[ chuckles, clears throat ]

24:26.719 --> 24:28.453
You did an interview in my apartment?

24:28.488 --> 24:31.590
- Thought this was a condo.
- In my apartment?!

24:31.625 --> 24:33.259
I-I mean, I said a lot
of nice things about you.

24:33.293 --> 24:34.560
- Tommy!
- They must've cut them out.

24:34.594 --> 24:35.961
<i>Why would you ... get out.</i>

24:36.029 --> 24:37.863
Get out now! Get out now.

24:39.733 --> 24:42.000
- Jane Rizzoli?
- Yes.

24:42.034 --> 24:46.771
You've been served.
[ sighs ]

24:50.041 --> 24:52.442
I can't ... I...

24:52.477 --> 24:57.447
- She sued me.
- Goodbye.

24:57.514 --> 24:58.614
Oh.

25:09.037 --> 25:12.273
<i>[ knock on door ]</i>

25:13.542 --> 25:15.508
<i>Vince... thanks for coming.</i>

25:15.543 --> 25:19.045
- Sure. Is she here?
- Yep.

25:19.080 --> 25:21.214
Upstairs taking a shower.

25:22.750 --> 25:27.121
This lawsuit looks like a boiler plate.
Thought they filed it fast.

25:27.155 --> 25:30.924
Boiler plate? 
So, it's bullshit?

25:30.958 --> 25:32.892
Sorry, I'm ... I'm upset.

25:32.927 --> 25:35.862
You're right.
You never know what a jury will do.

25:35.896 --> 25:38.230
- Poor Jane.
- You know, I liked it better

25:38.265 --> 25:41.199
before the computer media cloud stuff.

25:41.234 --> 25:43.501
Me, too. 
You could have a conversation.

25:43.736 --> 25:47.170
- You want some coffee?
- Love some.

25:47.204 --> 25:51.039
- You want a little irish whiskey in it?
- Sure, but skip the coffee.

25:51.073 --> 25:52.505
[ chuckles ]

25:52.539 --> 25:57.074
Half a million bucks?
That's what she wants?

25:57.108 --> 25:59.242
Can you believe it?

25:59.277 --> 26:01.811
Vince, Jane doesn't
have that kind of money

26:01.845 --> 26:03.279
unless she sells her condo.

26:03.313 --> 26:05.380
It won't come to that.
She was on the job.

26:05.415 --> 26:09.485
- The city has to cover legal costs.
- Well, I'm still gonna help her.

26:12.088 --> 26:13.388
You're a good mom.

26:13.456 --> 26:16.024
[ glasses clink ]

26:20.263 --> 26:24.466
- Oh, I didn't know you were in here.
- My back hurts.

26:24.500 --> 26:27.402
High cortisol levels from stress.

26:27.437 --> 26:29.771
Why would I be stressed?
[ chuckles ]

26:29.805 --> 26:34.541
Just a coffee-throwing
b-b-b-b-b-bitch.

26:34.576 --> 26:37.310
Stop. 
It was one moment in a life.

26:37.345 --> 26:39.212
One moment caught on tape.

26:39.246 --> 26:43.349
- Well, let it go. Ujjayi breath.
- "Ooh-jie" who?

26:43.416 --> 26:47.185
It's a deep, cleansing breath.
Just focus on the present.

26:47.253 --> 26:49.487
[ breathes deeply ] 
[ cellphone vibrating ]

26:49.521 --> 26:52.223
I'm trying, but you're vibrating.

26:52.257 --> 26:53.324
[ chuckles ]

26:53.358 --> 26:56.644
It's Susie. The particulate
found in the victim's

26:56.645 --> 26:59.930
head wound was
fiber-reinforced polymer.

26:59.964 --> 27:02.165
Is that animal, vegetable, or mineral?

27:02.199 --> 27:06.469
Mineral. It's a fine mixture
of glass, carbon, and basalt.

27:06.503 --> 27:08.838
- And what's that used for?
- High-tech applications.

27:08.872 --> 27:10.573
It's used as a structural component

27:10.607 --> 27:12.942
in everything from
skyscrapers to aircraft.

27:12.976 --> 27:15.110
High-tech murder weapon.

27:15.145 --> 27:18.513
Wonder if Leroy found something
and drug it into his basement.

27:18.548 --> 27:22.350
You're a very good Detective.
And a very good person...

27:22.385 --> 27:24.485
Once you've had your
coffee. [ chuckles ]

27:26.421 --> 27:28.623
Yeah, I let the little
things get to me today.

27:28.657 --> 27:30.257
We all do, Jane.

27:30.292 --> 27:34.461
Just take a deep breath
and stay in the present.

27:34.495 --> 27:36.363
[ breathes deeply ]

27:36.430 --> 27:39.399
[ cellphone vibrating ]
Why does work always know

27:39.433 --> 27:41.201
when I'm trying to stay in the present?

27:43.071 --> 27:45.405
Rizzoli.

27:45.440 --> 27:47.508
What? When?

27:47.575 --> 27:51.546
All right, get two more
uniforms over there. Thanks.

27:51.613 --> 27:53.114
What is it?

27:53.149 --> 27:55.317
Somebody tried to break
into Leroy's basement.

28:00.624 --> 28:02.025
[ elevator bell dings ]

28:02.059 --> 28:06.263
- All right, thank you.
- Morning.

28:06.297 --> 28:07.631
That was the sergeant
at the crime scene.

28:07.665 --> 28:10.600
They kept the flood lights
on all night. So far, so good.

28:10.635 --> 28:12.269
That's got to be our
killer, don't you think?

28:12.303 --> 28:14.138
And what is so valuable in there

28:14.172 --> 28:16.173
that you would risk getting caught?

28:16.208 --> 28:18.342
Good thing the guys on
watch were paying attention.

28:18.376 --> 28:20.210
Maybe Daniel was down there
looking for the same thing,

28:20.245 --> 28:22.946
and that's why he's dead.

28:24.449 --> 28:26.217
Who left these here?

28:26.251 --> 28:27.885
I don't know, but they'll get
sick of teasing you pretty soon.

28:27.986 --> 28:31.656
Ooh, it's still hot.
Thank you.

28:31.690 --> 28:34.258
<i>It's very thoughtful.
[ both chuckling ]</i>

28:34.293 --> 28:37.529
Did, uh, Frost and Frankie find anything
that could be the murder weapon?

28:37.563 --> 28:40.532
Maybe. You said high-tech?
They found something.

28:40.600 --> 28:43.102
CSRU is bringing it in for
Maura to have a look at.

28:43.170 --> 28:45.037
[ cellphone vibrating ]

28:45.072 --> 28:46.539
All right, this is Maura.

28:46.573 --> 28:49.208
She's confirmed it's made of
fiber-reinforced polymer ...

28:49.242 --> 28:51.143
the same stuff she found
in the victim's head wound.

28:51.177 --> 28:53.145
- Sounds like our murder weapon.
- Yeah.

28:53.179 --> 28:55.414
You want to be Claire or Maura?

28:55.482 --> 28:58.317
Doesn't matter, as long as you
don't throw the other one at me.

28:58.351 --> 29:00.185
[ chuckles sarcastically ] 
[ chuckles ]

29:00.220 --> 29:02.618
<i>- Good one.
- Thank you.</i>

29:03.323 --> 29:06.625
- Korsak: Any idea what it is?
- I'm not sure.

29:06.660 --> 29:08.327
It looks pretty small
to be the murder weapon.

29:08.395 --> 29:09.695
It's not the murder weapon,

29:09.730 --> 29:11.330
but it might be made
of the same materials.

29:11.365 --> 29:13.935
Yeah. It's really light.

29:13.969 --> 29:17.572
Stiffness and strength at a very
low weight. It's because of this.

29:17.606 --> 29:19.240
You see the honeycomb-like structure?

29:19.275 --> 29:23.478
Yeah, it looks like the marks
that were pounded into Daniel's head.

29:23.546 --> 29:25.080
Now, what the hell is it?

29:25.114 --> 29:27.649
You know, whatever it is,
it's made of highly complex

29:27.684 --> 29:29.651
and a unique combination of materials.

29:29.686 --> 29:32.522
You said high-tech applications?

29:32.556 --> 29:34.524
- Mm-hmm.
- I mean, it's a long shot,

29:34.558 --> 29:39.328
but what if we did a patent search,
find out what we're looking for?

29:44.303 --> 29:48.073
Two days in a hoarder's basement.
I'm officially claustrophobic.

29:48.107 --> 29:50.111
Ah, we're almost done.

29:50.145 --> 29:53.749
I don't believe this.
B.O., number 4?

29:55.818 --> 29:59.454
- Do you know whose skate this is?
- Can't be. No.

29:59.488 --> 30:02.657
- It's the right size.
- Did we just find Bobby Orr's skate?

30:02.725 --> 30:05.626
I think we did. 
[ both chuckle ]

30:05.661 --> 30:08.229
Hey, wait.

30:08.263 --> 30:10.531
You remember that neighbor guy
who tried to bring us lemonade?

30:10.565 --> 30:12.733
Yeah. 
Yeah, and he had that story

30:12.768 --> 30:15.336
about lending Leroy his hockey skates.

30:15.370 --> 30:17.739
- What guy brings lemonade?
- You're right.

30:17.773 --> 30:21.543
And if this really is Bobby Orr's skate,
 it's crazy valuable.

30:21.577 --> 30:24.145
What if Leroy's neighbor
was stealing something

30:24.246 --> 30:26.347
from the basement when the
garbage man surprised him?

30:26.448 --> 30:28.016
Maybe friendly neighbor

30:28.083 --> 30:29.617
is really friendly
neighborhood murderer.

30:29.652 --> 30:31.186
Which means we're looking
for the murder weapon

30:31.220 --> 30:32.853
in the wrong house.

30:40.256 --> 30:42.957
That's him ... Mac Hazlet. 

30:42.992 --> 30:45.360
He's quite the successful
e-bay entrepreneur.

30:45.394 --> 30:48.095
<i>Antiques, collectibles,
hockey memorabilia.</i>

30:48.129 --> 30:51.231
Started raking it in
about six months ago.

30:51.299 --> 30:53.233
Leroy broke his hip six months ago.

30:53.268 --> 30:55.435
Frost, see if you can find
the E.R. admissions report.

30:55.503 --> 30:57.038
You thinking Mac discovered

30:57.072 --> 30:58.973
Leroy's antiques road
show in his basement

30:59.007 --> 31:00.508
- and started stealing his stuff?
- Yep.

31:00.542 --> 31:04.712
Wow. Was Mac.
He's listed on the report.

31:04.746 --> 31:06.380
Says he heard Leroy's cries
for help and called 911.

31:06.481 --> 31:08.316
You know something?

31:08.350 --> 31:11.152
Mac needs to pick on
someone his own age.

31:17.827 --> 31:21.363
You sold Terry o'Reilly's hockey glove,
Phil Esposito's stick.

31:21.397 --> 31:23.865
You just listed one
of Bobby Orr's skates.

31:23.900 --> 31:26.468
The left one.
I wonder where the right one is.

31:26.502 --> 31:29.871
Be a lot more valuable as a pair.
I'm a Big Bruins fan.

31:29.906 --> 31:35.211
- Where do you find this great stuff?
- Um, uh, here and there.

31:35.245 --> 31:37.813
Uh, flea markets, private collectors.

31:37.847 --> 31:39.882
So, not next door in Leroy's basement?

31:39.950 --> 31:42.318
[ chuckles ]

31:42.352 --> 31:44.320
I took a few things.

31:44.354 --> 31:47.456
I mean, you know, it was just
sitting there collecting dust.

31:47.491 --> 31:49.375
I-I wanted to put it in the hands of

31:49.376 --> 31:51.260
guys like you who really appreciate it.

31:51.295 --> 31:53.896
Oh, that was really nice
of him, wasn't it, Sergeant?

31:53.931 --> 31:55.632
Korsak: It sure was. What do you think

31:55.633 --> 31:57.333
that murder weapon
you have would be worth

31:57.367 --> 31:59.001
to somebody that collects
that kind of stuff?

31:59.036 --> 32:02.238
What murder weapon?

32:03.407 --> 32:06.509
The metal club you used
to kill the garbage man.

32:06.543 --> 32:08.911
I didn't kill anybody.

32:08.945 --> 32:11.080
Our colleagues are tearing
apart your house as we speak.

32:11.114 --> 32:13.215
- You can't do that.
- A judge said we can.

32:13.249 --> 32:14.550
You could make it easy on everyone.

32:14.584 --> 32:15.951
Just tell us where the murder weapon is.

32:15.985 --> 32:19.488
- I-I'm not telling you crap.
- You're under arrest for larceny.

32:29.965 --> 32:32.933
7:59 A.M.
Do you know what that means?

32:32.968 --> 32:34.468
It was one minute before 8:00?

32:34.503 --> 32:38.005
- And what time do you go on duty?
- 8:00.

32:38.073 --> 32:41.441
The good news is, this is no
longer a police-brutality case.

32:41.476 --> 32:43.543
Oh, that is good news.

32:43.578 --> 32:46.179
- What's the bad news?
- It's a civil matter.

32:46.213 --> 32:48.381
And because you weren't on the clock,

32:48.415 --> 32:51.317
the city's refusing to indemnify you.

32:51.352 --> 32:55.421
You can't be serious.
So I'm on my own?

33:01.094 --> 33:04.096
Look at that ... another 17 cents.

33:04.130 --> 33:06.565
I wonder if F. Lee Bailey
will take your case now.

33:06.600 --> 33:07.967
Mm.

33:08.034 --> 33:10.302
If I tell him to shut up, do you
think he'll put it on youtube?

33:10.336 --> 33:13.972
I wouldn't put it past him.
Okay, where's Maura?

33:14.074 --> 33:16.174
I want to know what that lawyer said.

33:16.209 --> 33:20.111
- [ sighs ] Well?
- I brought Matcha tea.

33:20.146 --> 33:22.347
It's from Utashinai.
You want to try some?

33:22.414 --> 33:23.982
Maura, what did he say? 
[ coins rattle ]

33:24.016 --> 33:25.650
Oh, look, another 50 cents.

33:25.685 --> 33:28.253
Rizzoli, get over here
and help your customers.

33:28.320 --> 33:33.124
- Yes, Mr. Stanley.
- Okay, just tell me what he said.

33:33.158 --> 33:36.628
He said it would be expensive to defend.

33:36.662 --> 33:38.630
- I just spilled coffee.
- I know.

33:38.664 --> 33:42.133
It's a frivolous lawsuit,
but he looked at the video,

33:42.201 --> 33:45.070
and if she has medical expenses
or compensatory damages ...

33:45.137 --> 33:50.675
- For crying out loud.
- Just ... how much is it to hire him?

33:50.710 --> 33:53.011
He wants a $25,000 retainer.

33:53.046 --> 33:57.416
Oh, my god.
Maura, every cent I have is in my condo.

33:58.388 --> 34:00.275
<i>I know.</i>

34:01.453 --> 34:04.322
I know.
I could live in Leroy's basement.

34:04.356 --> 34:06.223
Oh, come on. Let me help you.

34:06.291 --> 34:08.192
You know, I'll just cash
out some mutual funds.

34:08.226 --> 34:10.027
No. I can't take your money.

34:10.061 --> 34:13.164
<i>- [ auto-tuned ] Don't touch me. 
- Don't look at that.</i>

34:13.197 --> 34:16.033
I can't believe I'm gonna
lose my home over this.

34:16.067 --> 34:18.668
<i> B-b-b-b-bitch.</i>

34:18.704 --> 34:20.471
Maura, look at her blouse.

34:22.041 --> 34:24.074
They can manufacture
an artificial heart,

34:24.110 --> 34:26.578
but they can't get a polyester
blend to drape properly.

34:26.646 --> 34:28.346
No.

34:28.380 --> 34:31.315
That.
You see it now?

34:31.384 --> 34:34.319
Her blouse is repelling
the droplets of coffee.

34:34.353 --> 34:38.322
Wait, that could be made
of a scald-proof nanofabric.

34:38.358 --> 34:40.225
Help for the fashion-challenged.

34:40.260 --> 34:44.063
Teflon-nanotube coating
is used on some textiles

34:44.097 --> 34:47.933
- to produce scald-proof fabrics.
- So, she set it up.

34:47.967 --> 34:50.069
She even had somebody 
there to tape it.

34:50.103 --> 34:51.737
You think she wanted
you to spill your coffee

34:51.771 --> 34:54.172
so she could sue?
But how'd she know you were a cop?

34:54.239 --> 34:56.274
- I'll be damned.
- What? What do you see?

34:56.309 --> 34:57.976
Whirls and ridges.

34:58.010 --> 34:59.744
Whoever videotaped it left a
fingerprint on the camera lens.

34:59.778 --> 35:02.714
We should run that.
[ computer chimes ]

35:02.748 --> 35:07.085
Yes!
Yes!

35:07.119 --> 35:09.087
Oh, yes!

35:09.121 --> 35:12.256
I found the patent.
I know what this is.

35:12.290 --> 35:14.225
It's a piece of a new type
of rotor blade from a drone.

35:14.259 --> 35:17.227
- From a drone?
- Yeah. Manufactured by JFP.

35:17.262 --> 35:19.496
Jarvis Flight Project.

35:19.531 --> 35:21.732
<i>That would explain
the honeycomb interior.</i>

35:21.766 --> 35:25.669
And the edge of the rotor blade
is consistent with the wound pattern.

35:25.704 --> 35:28.272
How does a piece of a drone
end up in Leroy's basement?

35:28.307 --> 35:32.009
Maybe he dragged it inside after
he shot it down with the bug zapper.

35:32.077 --> 35:35.446
E.M.P. would destroy the
drone's electronic system ...

35:35.481 --> 35:37.248
probably cause a power outage, too.

35:37.282 --> 35:39.250
Yeah, but do we know if that even works?

35:39.284 --> 35:42.320
- Oh, yeah. It works.
- Korsak: Really? How do you know that?

35:44.122 --> 35:46.090
Well ...

35:46.124 --> 35:47.658
Have anything to do
with the two cruisers

35:47.692 --> 35:49.493
who got their brains
fried at the crime scene?

35:49.528 --> 35:52.730
- I think I'll take the fifth.
- Hmm.

35:52.764 --> 35:55.566
Drones can be used for
corporate espionage.

35:55.600 --> 35:59.303
And Leroy was convinced that
he was being watched, spied on.

35:59.337 --> 36:02.339
Spy on an old man's house
with a million-dollar drone?

36:02.407 --> 36:04.774
Maybe they were spying
on the neighborhood.

36:04.809 --> 36:08.144
Frontload Tech just moved
its R&D offices right nearby.

36:08.178 --> 36:10.113
Yeah, but there would
be a ton of firewalls

36:10.147 --> 36:11.748
to protect proprietary information.

36:13.116 --> 36:15.051
[ beeping ]

36:15.086 --> 36:19.222
Yeah, but look at all these houses sold.
Frost, who lives around Leroy?

36:21.258 --> 36:24.193
Frontload Tech engineers.
A lot of them.

36:24.261 --> 36:27.798
That's it. You take your
phone and your computer home.

36:27.832 --> 36:31.168
If I wanted to steal, I would send
a drone, fly it over your home.

36:31.203 --> 36:33.037
It was doing a war-drive ...

36:33.071 --> 36:35.540
piggybacking on wi-fi networks
and downloading everything.

36:35.574 --> 36:39.378
- Frost, look up JFP's website.
- Got it right here.

36:39.412 --> 36:41.414
What else does JFP do?

36:41.448 --> 36:43.783
They offer
intelligence-gathering services.

36:43.817 --> 36:45.451
Look who's head of the division.

36:45.486 --> 36:48.555
We saw him outside Leroy's
house at the standoff.

36:48.589 --> 36:50.690
Jim Blackman ... former Navy Seal,

36:50.725 --> 36:53.460
specializes in
military-intelligence gathering.

36:53.494 --> 36:56.329
Said he was a neighbor.

36:58.432 --> 37:00.634
<i>Yeah, except he lives 20 miles away.</i>

37:00.668 --> 37:05.372
Could you track the drone sent
out back to Leroy's basement?

37:05.406 --> 37:07.374
Yes. It had a GPS locator.

37:07.408 --> 37:09.209
This is a picture of
Jim at the crime scene.

37:09.244 --> 37:10.611
He told me he had to get to the office,

37:10.645 --> 37:13.063
but he looks a hell of a lot
more interested about what's

37:13.064 --> 37:15.482
going on inside Leroy's house
than he does in getting to work.

37:15.517 --> 37:17.752
The break-in last night.

37:17.820 --> 37:19.688
It was a huge risk, but
there must be something

37:19.689 --> 37:21.556
inside that house that
ties him to the murder.

37:21.590 --> 37:24.859
But what?
I mean, we went through everything.

37:25.193 --> 37:28.696
What did Leroy have in his
pockets when we brought him in?

37:31.166 --> 37:34.434
69 cents, package of
tums, a rabbit's foot.

37:34.469 --> 37:39.572
And a miniature hard drive.
Can you punch in on that?

37:39.607 --> 37:44.410
It's ... it's hard to see,
but I'm pretty sure it's stamped "JFP."

37:46.880 --> 37:50.216
JFP ... Jim Blackman's
drone-manufacturing company.

37:50.250 --> 37:55.588
We need to find Jim.
I'm gonna make sure Leroy's safe first.

37:55.622 --> 37:59.125
Hey, this is Detective Rizzoli.
I need a status report on Leroy Grovner.

38:02.729 --> 38:04.763
He's been released.

38:13.822 --> 38:17.291
[ indistinct conversation in distance ]

38:20.028 --> 38:21.328
Clear.

38:21.363 --> 38:23.231
<i>Leroy: Put it down ... please!</i>

38:24.733 --> 38:27.135
<i>I don't know what you want.</i>

38:29.705 --> 38:33.141
<i>- Jim: Where's the hard drive you stole?
- Stop it.</i>

38:33.176 --> 38:36.245
<i>- Tell me where it is!
- Leave me alone!</i>

38:36.279 --> 38:39.248
- You're the reason your friend is dead.
- You shouldn't have killed Daniel.

38:39.282 --> 38:42.350
And you shouldn't have shot
down my drone and taken it apart.

38:42.385 --> 38:46.621
Now, where is it?
Where's the hard drive you stole?

38:46.689 --> 38:48.724
- Police have it.
- You're a liar!

38:48.758 --> 38:50.993
You tell me where it is 
or you're a dead man.

38:52.629 --> 38:54.363
Jim, it's over. Put the gun down.

38:54.397 --> 38:57.634
No. Don't move or I'll
blow the old man's head off.

38:57.668 --> 38:58.968
Let's all just calm down.

38:59.003 --> 39:00.770
Like I said, Jim, it's over.

39:00.805 --> 39:02.773
I'm not going down.
I'm gonna take you with me.

39:02.807 --> 39:05.175
- What? With Leroy's shotgun?
- Damn straight.

39:06.878 --> 39:09.013
Leroy, you load that
like you did before?

39:09.047 --> 39:12.149
- Sure did.
- You're a military man, Jim.

39:12.183 --> 39:16.053
You ought to recognize the difference
between live ammo and blanks.

39:20.225 --> 39:21.658
[ breathing heavily ]

39:23.695 --> 39:24.928
[ grunts ]

39:24.962 --> 39:28.065
That's for Daniel, you miserable yo-yo.

39:31.069 --> 39:34.405
[ coughs ] Come on, Jim.
Quit your whining.

39:34.439 --> 39:36.640
Leroy, you okay?

39:38.777 --> 39:43.214
All my stuff.
My whole ... my whole life.

39:43.248 --> 39:46.150
- It's all ... it's all gone.
- I-it's not gone, Leroy.

39:46.185 --> 39:47.752
We'll get your stuff back.

39:49.789 --> 39:51.423
Yeah.

39:53.493 --> 39:55.094
[ cellphone vibrates ]

39:55.128 --> 39:59.725
We got a hit on that fingerprint.
You recognize that name?

39:59.726 --> 40:01.367
Yeah. I sure do.

40:05.907 --> 40:09.276
<i>I was thinking desert tones
with a pop of cactus green.</i>

40:09.310 --> 40:11.111
<i>What do you think?</i>

40:11.145 --> 40:14.481
I think you're a little too
far East for a Southwest decor.

40:14.516 --> 40:18.452
- Especially in a historic building.
- Jane, I-I can explain.

40:18.487 --> 40:21.255
To a judge. What?
You did this for my condo?

40:21.290 --> 40:23.808
- That's crazy.
- It's even crazier to leave your

40:23.809 --> 40:26.727
fingerprints on the camera lens,
and that's all over youtube, too.

40:26.762 --> 40:30.698
It was, uh, Gil's idea.
I was happy living on the ground floor.

40:30.766 --> 40:32.333
Oh, right.

40:32.367 --> 40:34.401
[ mockingly ] "Baby, please,
could we convert the third floor?

40:34.436 --> 40:38.105
"It's the nicest spot in the building.
Please, please, please?"

40:38.139 --> 40:42.409
- I do not talk like that.
- You see what I'm dealing with? [ sighs ]

40:42.443 --> 40:45.145
Okay. We'll get you separate cells.
You're under arrest for fraud.

40:45.179 --> 40:47.013
<i>I cannot believe I hooked up with you!</i>

40:47.048 --> 40:49.883
<i>- Gil: You hooked up with me. Right.
- Oh...</i>

40:53.521 --> 40:55.021
Hold on, I want to show you something.

40:55.056 --> 40:57.157
- Come here.
- What?

40:57.191 --> 40:59.025
If I'm in it, I don't want to see it.

40:59.060 --> 41:02.362
<i>- I'm sorry.
- Why do you say that?</i>

41:02.397 --> 41:08.168
<i>I-I thought you weren't a-a
nice lady, but ... but you are.</i>

41:08.203 --> 41:11.806
You know, we live in
a dual-party consent state.

41:11.840 --> 41:14.075
I could sue you for secretly taping me.

41:14.109 --> 41:15.910
Go ahead and try.
 I have a good attorney.

41:15.945 --> 41:19.014
- It has 11 hits, Maura.
- Give it some time.

41:19.049 --> 41:21.350
What? For the "Europeans"
to discover it?

41:21.384 --> 41:24.420
Okay, maybe we need to spice
